00:11:10.120 --> 00:11:14.120
And they had butcher shops in Cardiff, Clifton Street.

00:11:14.120 --> 00:11:15.120
Yes.

00:11:15.120 --> 00:11:16.120
There was a big butchery in there.

00:11:16.120 --> 00:11:19.120
And that was their business, more or less, you know.

00:11:19.120 --> 00:11:21.120
So, butchery shop.

00:11:21.120 --> 00:11:22.120
Yes.

00:11:22.120 --> 00:11:23.120
Butcher shop.

00:11:23.120 --> 00:11:26.120
So when did the farm come into the...

00:11:26.120 --> 00:11:31.120
Well, Wynneford, he wasn't keen on the butchery shop, so he went farming then.

00:11:31.120 --> 00:11:35.120
So he took over, took sluice and rented sluice.

00:11:35.120 --> 00:11:36.120
Oh, right.

00:11:36.120 --> 00:11:37.120
And then, of course, the milk.

00:11:37.120 --> 00:11:41.120
And then they used to have a milk round with a milk van and everything.

00:11:41.120 --> 00:11:45.120
And Dew Wynne used to go occasionally when his father had a meeting up in London, but

00:11:45.120 --> 00:11:50.120
he wasn't so keen on the milk round.

00:11:50.120 --> 00:11:54.120
But he used to do it when his father had to go to London for meetings with the drainage

00:11:54.120 --> 00:11:55.120
port and that, you know.

00:11:55.120 --> 00:11:58.120
So why did they have meetings in London?

00:11:58.120 --> 00:12:00.120
I don't know, really.

00:12:01.120 --> 00:12:05.120
And of course they used to have the meetings out at Magad, didn't they?

00:12:05.120 --> 00:12:06.120
Yeah.

00:12:06.120 --> 00:12:07.120
That's the place.

00:12:07.120 --> 00:12:08.120
Is it Magad?

00:12:08.120 --> 00:12:09.120
Yes, Magad, isn't it?

00:12:09.120 --> 00:12:10.120
They used to have the...

00:12:10.120 --> 00:12:11.120
Oh, Nash.

00:12:11.120 --> 00:12:12.120
Nash, rather.

00:12:12.120 --> 00:12:13.120
That's right.

00:12:13.120 --> 00:12:14.120
Pie Corner.

00:12:14.120 --> 00:12:15.120
That's right, Pie Corner.

00:12:15.120 --> 00:12:16.120
Yeah.

00:12:16.120 --> 00:12:17.120
Yes, Nash.

00:12:17.120 --> 00:12:18.120
Yes, yeah.

00:12:18.120 --> 00:12:19.120
So...

00:12:19.120 --> 00:12:23.120
So was it always a dairy farm then, the sluice farm?

00:12:23.120 --> 00:12:24.120
Yes, yes.

00:12:24.120 --> 00:12:26.120
Yes, they had cows and everything.

00:12:26.120 --> 00:12:27.120
And sheep.

00:12:27.120 --> 00:12:31.120
And then we moved up here later.

00:12:31.120 --> 00:12:34.120
And then they moved there, but then they went out to the cows.

00:12:34.120 --> 00:12:37.120
And so the Andros only got the sheep at the moment.

00:12:37.120 --> 00:12:40.120
So then you met Dilwyn.

00:12:40.120 --> 00:12:41.120
Three young farmers.

00:12:41.120 --> 00:12:42.120
Three young farmers.

00:12:42.120 --> 00:12:46.120
And so where did you marry, actually?

00:12:46.120 --> 00:12:47.120
In Coorkean O'Church.

00:12:47.120 --> 00:12:48.120
Oh, did you?

00:12:48.120 --> 00:12:49.120
It's a dear little church, yes.

00:12:49.120 --> 00:12:50.120
Yeah.

00:12:50.120 --> 00:12:51.120
It's a house now that's been turned into...

00:12:51.120 --> 00:12:52.120
Yes, Coorkean...

00:12:52.120 --> 00:12:53.120
Do you know...

00:12:53.120 --> 00:13:00.120
Well, you know the main one I said about with this article is you're turned down for Coorkean

00:13:00.120 --> 00:13:01.120
O'Church for the golf course.

00:13:01.120 --> 00:13:02.120
Yes.

00:13:02.120 --> 00:13:03.120
And it's just before you get to the golf course.

00:13:03.120 --> 00:13:05.120
Or just after the golf course, sorry.

00:13:05.120 --> 00:13:06.120
On the right.

00:13:06.120 --> 00:13:09.120
On the left-hand side you've got a little lane up to the church.

00:13:09.120 --> 00:13:10.120
Really?

00:13:10.120 --> 00:13:12.120
Oh, I don't think I've been to the church.

00:13:12.120 --> 00:13:13.120
Oh, I don't think...

00:13:13.120 --> 00:13:14.120
It's a house now.

00:13:14.120 --> 00:13:15.120
It's...

00:13:15.120 --> 00:13:16.120
Was it a chapel then?

00:13:16.120 --> 00:13:17.120
Or was it a chapel?

00:13:17.120 --> 00:13:18.120
No, a church.

00:13:18.120 --> 00:13:19.120
Really?

00:13:19.120 --> 00:13:20.120
Yeah, Coorkean O'Church.

00:13:20.120 --> 00:13:21.120
Oh, I have to go back that way afterwards.

00:13:21.120 --> 00:13:22.120
I might go and have a look.

00:13:22.120 --> 00:13:23.120
Yes, yes, yes.

00:13:23.120 --> 00:13:24.120
I had no idea.

00:13:24.120 --> 00:13:27.120
And I think there's three or four houses there.

00:13:27.120 --> 00:13:32.120
Because there was a farm next to it but they've gone into homesteads, you see.

00:13:32.120 --> 00:13:36.120
So then, so did you then start your married life at Soos Farm?

00:13:36.120 --> 00:13:37.120
Yes.

00:13:37.120 --> 00:13:39.120
You moved in with your in-laws?

00:13:39.120 --> 00:13:40.120
Yes.

00:13:40.120 --> 00:13:41.120
No, no, they moved, they built a house.

00:13:41.120 --> 00:13:43.120
Do you see the house on the side there?

00:13:43.120 --> 00:13:44.120
Yes.

00:13:44.120 --> 00:13:45.120
They built that.

00:13:45.120 --> 00:13:50.120
And then we went into the farmhouse and they built that and went into there.

00:13:50.120 --> 00:13:52.120
So this would have been, what, the mid-50s?

00:13:52.120 --> 00:13:53.120
Yes, 57.

00:13:53.120 --> 00:13:54.120
57?

00:13:54.120 --> 00:13:55.120
Yes.

00:13:55.120 --> 00:13:58.120
So, erm, so what was the farm doing then?

00:13:58.120 --> 00:13:59.120
Was it...

00:13:59.120 --> 00:14:00.120
Er, milk.

00:14:00.120 --> 00:14:01.120
Milk.

00:14:01.120 --> 00:14:02.120
Milk and milk round.

00:14:02.120 --> 00:14:03.120
Yeah.

00:14:03.120 --> 00:14:06.120
Yeah, and they'd fill the bottles, you know, and wash the bottles in and in the little

00:14:06.120 --> 00:14:07.120
shed that was there.

00:14:07.120 --> 00:14:08.120
Yeah.

00:14:08.120 --> 00:14:09.120
That's erm...

00:14:09.120 --> 00:14:12.120
Yes, I think I've got a photograph here.

00:14:12.120 --> 00:14:13.120
Excuse me.

00:14:13.120 --> 00:14:16.120
How many cows did you have, Margaret?

00:14:16.120 --> 00:14:19.120
How many cows did you have?

00:14:19.120 --> 00:14:22.120
Er, well not like they've got today, they've got hundreds today, haven't they?

00:14:22.120 --> 00:14:23.120
Yeah.

00:14:23.120 --> 00:14:24.120
But they've really been 125.

00:14:24.120 --> 00:14:25.120
But that's still...

00:14:25.120 --> 00:14:28.120
Which is quite, you know, big for those days, I suppose, wasn't it?

00:14:28.120 --> 00:14:29.120
Yeah.

00:14:29.120 --> 00:14:32.120
Nice to get a photograph here, I think, aren't they?

00:14:32.120 --> 00:14:33.120
Yeah.

00:14:33.120 --> 00:14:36.120
And that wasn't all hand-milked, was it?

00:14:36.120 --> 00:14:38.120
Was that all milked by hand?

00:14:38.120 --> 00:14:45.120
Well, it was years ago and then they went in with the machines then, you know.

00:14:45.120 --> 00:14:48.120
This is a photograph of Slough's house.

00:14:48.120 --> 00:14:51.120
This was before 1963.

00:14:51.120 --> 00:14:54.120
That's where it was when I used to live there, you see.

00:14:54.120 --> 00:14:55.120
Oh, crikey.

00:14:55.120 --> 00:14:56.120
There was a milk van right there.

00:14:56.120 --> 00:14:57.120
Yeah.

00:14:57.120 --> 00:15:00.120
A dairy there where they used to wash the bottles.

00:15:00.120 --> 00:15:01.120
Yeah.

00:15:01.120 --> 00:15:02.120
Cows used to go into there.

00:15:02.120 --> 00:15:03.120
Yeah.

00:15:03.120 --> 00:15:04.120
And then this was the garden.

00:15:04.120 --> 00:15:06.120
I mean, Anne's got a beautiful garden down there now.

00:15:06.120 --> 00:15:07.120
Wow.

00:15:07.120 --> 00:15:09.120
And then there was just a shed where we kept chickens.

00:15:09.120 --> 00:15:10.120
Yes.

00:15:10.120 --> 00:15:14.120
Erm, so it all altered, of course, because all this is buildings, you know.

00:15:14.120 --> 00:15:15.120
This has all changed, hasn't it?

00:15:15.120 --> 00:15:16.120
Yeah, all definitely.

00:15:16.120 --> 00:15:17.120
I mean, it's all built up.

00:15:17.120 --> 00:15:18.120
Yes.

00:15:18.120 --> 00:15:19.120
Very rural then.

00:15:19.120 --> 00:15:20.120
Yes, yes, yes.

00:15:20.120 --> 00:15:21.120
It was.

00:15:21.120 --> 00:15:22.120
Crikey.

00:15:22.120 --> 00:15:26.120
And then in this wheelchair, which was his own, that's where they built the house.

00:15:26.120 --> 00:15:27.120
You can see Wyvern.

00:15:27.120 --> 00:15:28.120
Oh.

00:15:28.120 --> 00:15:29.120
You know, they built that there.

00:15:29.120 --> 00:15:33.120
Did they build that because Dilwyn was getting married?

00:15:33.120 --> 00:15:34.120
Yes, yes.

00:15:34.120 --> 00:15:36.120
They built that to go in there.

00:15:36.120 --> 00:15:40.120
And erm, oh, but I was only thinking the other day.

00:15:40.120 --> 00:15:42.120
I think it was about 90.

00:15:42.120 --> 00:15:44.120
Oh, I've forgotten the money.

00:15:44.120 --> 00:15:48.120
I'm not sure I was thinking about how much it cost the other day.

00:15:48.120 --> 00:15:53.120
The bridge cost me more to get across the reed to get to the house than the house, I think.

00:15:53.120 --> 00:15:54.120
Really?

00:15:54.120 --> 00:15:55.120
Yes, it was.

00:15:55.120 --> 00:15:56.120
You forget about that, don't you?

00:15:56.120 --> 00:15:57.120
Yes, you do.

00:15:57.120 --> 00:15:58.120
You have to get across the reed.

00:15:58.120 --> 00:15:59.120
That's true.

00:15:59.120 --> 00:16:00.120
Yes, yes.

00:16:00.120 --> 00:16:04.120
So what were your first impressions when you moved down there and started married life?

00:16:04.120 --> 00:16:08.120
Erm, well, I used to go back and forth there before we were actually married, you know,

00:16:08.120 --> 00:16:12.120
and have supper and things with Mother-in-law and that.

00:16:12.120 --> 00:16:18.120
And erm, yes, well I liked it very much because we had ground with Berry Hill.

00:16:18.120 --> 00:16:21.120
We had two fields on the moors, as we call them.

00:16:21.120 --> 00:16:22.120
Okay, yes.

00:16:22.120 --> 00:16:28.120
We rented those and erm, so it wasn't any different for me really, you know.

00:16:28.120 --> 00:16:29.120
Yeah.

00:16:29.120 --> 00:16:31.120
And then of course we used to go to Young Farmers there.

00:16:31.120 --> 00:16:33.120
We used to go to Young Farmers Club in St Melons.

00:16:33.120 --> 00:16:34.120
Did you?

00:16:34.120 --> 00:16:35.120
Yes, yes.

00:16:35.120 --> 00:16:37.120
In the chapel there, I used to hold the Young Farmers meetings.

00:16:37.120 --> 00:16:38.120
Yeah.

00:16:38.120 --> 00:16:39.120
But erm, oh yes.

00:16:39.120 --> 00:16:40.120
So I enjoyed life.

00:16:40.120 --> 00:16:41.120
So you were a farmer's wife.

00:16:41.120 --> 00:16:49.120
So I've spoken to lots of farmers and erm, so as a farmer's wife, would you, would you

00:16:49.120 --> 00:16:54.120
have been aware of and concerned with all the reams and the maintenance and stuff?

00:16:54.120 --> 00:16:59.120
I mean, I guess what I'm trying to ask is, was there very much a clear, this was what

00:16:59.120 --> 00:17:03.120
the woman did and this is what the men did, or was it all mixed up?

00:17:04.120 --> 00:17:10.120
Well I think, I used to enjoy going out and feeding calves and things and that, you know.

00:17:10.120 --> 00:17:14.120
And then when I was born, we used to put him in the plan, put him in the corner of the

00:17:14.120 --> 00:17:19.120
milking shed and he'd be sat there, you know, watching the cows coming in and out and all

00:17:19.120 --> 00:17:20.120
that.

00:17:20.120 --> 00:17:24.120
And before we had a parlour that was, the milking parlour type of thing, you know, where

00:17:24.120 --> 00:17:26.120
you could get up and in and mushing.

00:17:26.120 --> 00:17:30.120
But erm, yeah, I've always been, I've always been interested outside.

00:17:30.120 --> 00:17:35.120
Because I used to spend quite a bit of time before we went to Langhorst with my grandparents

00:17:35.120 --> 00:17:38.120
at Newhouse Farm, Pantague.

00:17:38.120 --> 00:17:39.120
Yeah.

00:17:39.120 --> 00:17:42.120
You know, just go out there and stay when I was a little tot, you know.

00:17:42.120 --> 00:17:46.120
Put me on the bus and you put my aunt with me, me and you in.

00:17:46.120 --> 00:17:47.120
How lovely.

00:17:47.120 --> 00:17:48.120
Yeah.

00:17:48.120 --> 00:17:51.120
So did you ever get involved in the bottling of milk down there?

00:17:51.120 --> 00:17:56.120
I used to have sometimes, and that helped, erm, my father probably used to, you know,

00:17:56.120 --> 00:17:57.120
mostly he'd do that.

00:17:57.120 --> 00:17:59.120
I'd have to come back off the road.

00:17:59.120 --> 00:18:04.120
And then wash the bottles and get them ready then to fill up the next morning.

00:18:04.120 --> 00:18:06.120
You know, it's, erm, yeah.

00:18:06.120 --> 00:18:07.120
Oh yes.

00:18:07.120 --> 00:18:11.120
Oh yes, I've had a very enjoyable life really.

00:18:11.120 --> 00:18:13.120
You can tell that, it shows in your face.

00:18:13.120 --> 00:18:14.120
It's lovely.

00:18:14.120 --> 00:18:15.120
Yeah, it does.

00:18:15.120 --> 00:18:16.120
What about the poultry?

00:18:16.120 --> 00:18:18.120
Was that an important part of the family?

00:18:18.120 --> 00:18:23.120
Yeah, we used to sell eggs on the milk farm quite a lot, you know.

00:18:23.120 --> 00:18:28.120
And then if there was any surplus eggs then, I used to bring them to the husband brothers

00:18:28.120 --> 00:18:36.120
who used to have, erm, well, I don't know, what do you call it, an egg centre that they

00:18:36.120 --> 00:18:39.120
would have eggs and then they'd take them out on different rounds.

00:18:39.120 --> 00:18:41.120
Where were the husband brothers based?

00:18:41.120 --> 00:18:43.120
It's, erm, Lisbon.

00:18:43.120 --> 00:18:44.120
Oh really?

00:18:44.120 --> 00:18:45.120
Yes, yes.

00:18:45.120 --> 00:18:47.120
But that's all different now altogether.

00:18:47.120 --> 00:18:50.120
You know, places change, don't they?

00:18:50.120 --> 00:18:51.120
Yeah.

00:18:51.120 --> 00:18:55.120
Well it's interesting, look at the new photograph, because you must have seen enormous change

00:18:55.120 --> 00:18:57.120
in your lifetime down there.

00:18:57.120 --> 00:19:02.120
Oh yes, yeah, especially now, more buildings up for stock and everything, you know.

00:19:02.120 --> 00:19:03.120
Yeah.

00:19:03.120 --> 00:19:07.120
And, erm, I mean I used to try and keep it well clean, tidy and all this business.

00:19:07.120 --> 00:19:09.120
And we used to have a boy living in then, you see.

00:19:09.120 --> 00:19:10.120
Did you?

00:19:10.120 --> 00:19:15.120
Yes, yes, you know the, erm, excuse me, you know the kitchen.

00:19:15.120 --> 00:19:17.120
You're going for the back door, don't you?

00:19:17.120 --> 00:19:20.120
Well that's the dining room, the kitchen for every day.

00:19:20.120 --> 00:19:21.120
Yeah.

00:19:21.120 --> 00:19:22.120
Then there's the kitchen, isn't there?

00:19:22.120 --> 00:19:23.120
Yeah.

00:19:23.120 --> 00:19:24.120
Then there's the other room.

00:19:24.120 --> 00:19:25.120
We used to have a boy living in there.

00:19:25.120 --> 00:19:26.120
Did you?

00:19:26.120 --> 00:19:30.120
Yes, yeah, and he had his bed in there and there was a stove in the corner.

00:19:30.120 --> 00:19:33.120
We used to have for the fire and he had an armchair.

00:19:33.120 --> 00:19:34.120
Yeah.

00:19:34.120 --> 00:19:35.120
He always ate with us.

00:19:35.120 --> 00:19:36.120
Yeah.

00:19:36.120 --> 00:19:39.120
And, erm, yes, so we always had a boy living in.

00:19:39.120 --> 00:19:41.120
And who was he?

00:19:41.120 --> 00:19:43.120
Was it a series of people or?

00:19:43.120 --> 00:19:48.120
Erm, well yes, different, we had a few from St. Brides that didn't live in, they came

00:19:48.120 --> 00:19:51.120
back and forth, which is, you know, from Cocoonia.

00:19:52.120 --> 00:19:57.120
But a couple of, they actually lived in there, you know, with us and they'd eat with us and

00:19:57.120 --> 00:19:58.120
all this business, you know.

00:19:58.120 --> 00:20:03.120
But, erm, I mean he had a television, well not a television, a wireless one, but he did

00:20:03.120 --> 00:20:05.120
have a television towards the end.

00:20:05.120 --> 00:20:08.120
And, erm, yes, we always had a boy living in.

00:20:08.120 --> 00:20:13.120
I suppose the farm could support that, whereas it would be difficult to do that today, wouldn't

00:20:13.120 --> 00:20:14.120
it?

00:20:14.120 --> 00:20:18.120
Well I suppose, yes, it's different, it's the different ideas today, isn't it?

00:20:18.120 --> 00:20:19.120
Yeah.

00:20:19.120 --> 00:20:21.120
Different world today, really.

00:20:21.120 --> 00:20:24.120
It's a strange lot to really be farming, isn't it?

00:20:24.120 --> 00:20:26.120
But did you have sheep then?

00:20:26.120 --> 00:20:32.120
Yes, we had some sheep, yeah, pet lambs and something, you know, feed those and, yes,

00:20:32.120 --> 00:20:36.120
I can't remember how many sheep, we didn't have so many sheep as well, no, naturally,

00:20:36.120 --> 00:20:39.120
because we had the dairying as well, you see.

00:20:39.120 --> 00:20:46.120
It's, erm, yes, oh yes, I've enjoyed my life up until now.

00:20:47.120 --> 00:20:51.120
So Antem used to go up onto the seawall and bring the sheep in on ponies.

00:20:51.120 --> 00:20:52.120
Yes.

00:20:52.120 --> 00:20:54.120
Did you ever get involved with that?

00:20:54.120 --> 00:20:56.120
No, not really, no, no.

00:20:56.120 --> 00:21:04.120
Yes, we'd put sheep over on the seawall and then, erm, Doreen, Derek's father, Philip,

00:21:04.120 --> 00:21:09.120
would come over and he'd have this horse and a little trap thing, you know, and they'd

00:21:09.120 --> 00:21:13.120
sit in there and then they'd go up then to get onto the horse and to bring the sheep

00:21:13.120 --> 00:21:15.120
up and all this business, you know.

00:21:15.120 --> 00:21:20.120
And then one day, erm, I don't know what happened, but anyhow, the pony started kicking

00:21:20.120 --> 00:21:25.120
the bottom of the possum and of course got out of the, out of the showers and left these

00:21:25.120 --> 00:21:30.120
four or five of them and the possum went backwards while it was suffering.

00:21:30.120 --> 00:21:32.120
What, backwards down the slope?

00:21:32.120 --> 00:21:34.120
Well, it went back, it went back, back, you know.

00:21:34.120 --> 00:21:36.120
Oh, I see, because the horse had gone.

00:21:36.120 --> 00:21:38.120
There were the showers hanging over them.

00:21:38.120 --> 00:21:39.120
Were they OK?

00:21:39.120 --> 00:21:44.120
Well, they were all right and the dog jumped out a bit quick and the dog was in as well.

00:21:44.120 --> 00:21:49.120
Oh, OK, yeah, they used to come over every Sunday and go down and see the sheep and all

00:21:49.120 --> 00:21:52.120
sorts of those, I don't know, pretty much.

00:21:52.120 --> 00:21:54.120
Because the sheep used to graze on the other side of it.

00:21:54.120 --> 00:21:56.120
Yes, yes, hmm, hmm.

00:21:56.120 --> 00:21:57.120
So.

00:21:57.120 --> 00:22:01.120
Until, like, erm, the tide used to come in so far, you know.

00:22:01.120 --> 00:22:02.120
Yeah.

00:22:02.120 --> 00:22:06.120
But they hired the, erm, I think they hired the bank then.

00:22:06.120 --> 00:22:12.120
Erm, yes, they did hire it because of course the sea, the water was coming, the sea was

00:22:12.120 --> 00:22:14.120
getting in higher, wasn't it, you know.

00:22:14.120 --> 00:22:17.120
Because you're very close to the seawall there, aren't you?

00:22:17.120 --> 00:22:19.120
Oh, yes, it's only the field really, isn't it?

00:22:19.120 --> 00:22:20.120
Yes.

00:22:20.120 --> 00:22:21.120
The field across.

00:22:21.120 --> 00:22:22.120
Did you ever experience the water coming over?

00:22:22.120 --> 00:22:27.120
You see it sometimes if it was very rough, just splashing up a bit, you know.

00:22:27.120 --> 00:22:33.120
But, erm, you know, I never had the thought in mind of thinking, oh gosh, I hope it doesn't

00:22:33.120 --> 00:22:34.120
come over there.

00:22:34.120 --> 00:22:35.120
I never thought of that.

00:22:35.120 --> 00:22:36.120
No.

00:22:36.120 --> 00:22:37.120
Which I suppose it does.

00:22:37.120 --> 00:22:41.120
It has, well, it has in some places over the years, hasn't it, you see.

00:22:41.120 --> 00:22:43.120
Do you ever use the shore where the sheet grates?

00:22:43.120 --> 00:22:46.120
Is there like a picnic spot when you had children when they were little?

00:22:46.120 --> 00:22:52.120
Yeah, we used to go over there and, erm, like, a lot of the, have you been over there?

00:22:52.120 --> 00:22:54.120
You've been over there, of course.

00:22:54.120 --> 00:22:55.120
Hmm.

00:22:55.120 --> 00:22:58.120
I haven't been over there for years really, so I don't know what it's like.

00:22:58.120 --> 00:23:02.120
But we used to have little, little, what's the name of the water coming in?

00:23:02.120 --> 00:23:04.120
Where there's been bits and digits.

00:23:04.120 --> 00:23:05.120
Yeah, like rivulets.

00:23:05.120 --> 00:23:06.120
Yes, yes, yes.

00:23:06.120 --> 00:23:07.120
Hmm.

00:23:07.120 --> 00:23:10.120
Yeah, yes, we used to go over there with our neighbours.

00:23:10.120 --> 00:23:13.120
Edinsons Neckardt Farm, Slough's Farm that would be.

00:23:13.120 --> 00:23:15.120
The one just on the side of the road.

00:23:15.120 --> 00:23:20.120
And, yes, we'd go over there for picnics and, er, yeah, we used to have a, you know, now

00:23:20.120 --> 00:23:22.120
and again have a good time.

00:23:22.120 --> 00:23:30.120
Was it, was it, erm, er, was there a real sense of community there then?

00:23:30.120 --> 00:23:34.120
Er, down the village, yeah, erm, even the village itself.

00:23:34.120 --> 00:23:35.120
Yeah.

00:23:35.120 --> 00:23:41.120
Oh yes, because those, those opposite the hall, those are all built, you see, erm, because

00:23:41.120 --> 00:23:45.120
when I went down there first there was no houses there then, you know, so they'd been

00:23:45.120 --> 00:23:48.120
built and at the back of the hall is a little cul-de-sac.

00:23:48.120 --> 00:23:49.120
Yeah.

00:23:49.120 --> 00:23:52.120
That's the council houses further over.

00:23:52.120 --> 00:23:54.120
They were, they were there when I went down.

00:23:54.120 --> 00:23:55.120
Hmm.

00:23:55.120 --> 00:23:58.120
And different houses had been built around there, you know.

00:23:58.120 --> 00:24:03.120
Yes, oh it's nice to live, I've been, I'm quite upset really because WI had been a

00:24:03.120 --> 00:24:05.120
member for 62 years down there.

00:24:05.120 --> 00:24:06.120
Have you?

00:24:06.120 --> 00:24:07.120
Yes.

00:24:07.120 --> 00:24:10.120
And, er, I used to take my mother-in-law because she didn't drive, Deryn's mother

00:24:10.120 --> 00:24:11.120
didn't drive.

00:24:11.120 --> 00:24:17.120
So, and then after lunch we'd go down on the, er, the second Tuesday of the month, I used

00:24:17.120 --> 00:24:21.120
to pick her up and we'd go down, because she was president at that time, and there was

00:24:21.120 --> 00:24:26.120
the back, the old black stove, I don't know if you've seen the old black stove, it was

00:24:26.120 --> 00:24:27.120
like that.

00:24:27.120 --> 00:24:28.120
In the village hall?

00:24:28.120 --> 00:24:29.120
In the village hall.

00:24:29.120 --> 00:24:34.120
And then put the chairs and tables up, and then go back then and I'd pick her up then

00:24:34.120 --> 00:24:36.120
at the tea then to go to WI.

00:24:36.120 --> 00:24:39.120
And, er, yes we did that for years.

00:24:39.120 --> 00:24:43.120
Erm, and then I used to have the milk van then, I had the milk van for a couple of,

00:24:43.120 --> 00:24:49.120
oh for about a week or more in the afternoons, to go to, er, a place in Bremne to get a

00:24:49.120 --> 00:24:50.120
sanding machine.

00:24:50.120 --> 00:24:55.120
And, er, put in the back there and come, and then redo the floor, you know, sand, get the

00:24:55.120 --> 00:24:57.120
floor all nice and, well, slim you know.

00:24:57.120 --> 00:24:58.120
Yeah?

00:24:58.120 --> 00:24:59.120
Oh, we've had some good times down there.

00:24:59.120 --> 00:25:00.120
Really good times.

00:25:00.120 --> 00:25:05.120
So somebody was telling me that St. Price WI used to have a canning machine.

00:25:05.120 --> 00:25:06.120
Yes.

00:25:06.120 --> 00:25:07.120
Do you know about that?

00:25:07.120 --> 00:25:09.120
Yes, yes, and Mother Prosser had it.

00:25:09.120 --> 00:25:11.120
Now where it is I don't know.

00:25:11.120 --> 00:25:14.120
Yes, because we used to put fruit into our own canning.

00:25:14.120 --> 00:25:15.120
Yes.

00:25:15.120 --> 00:25:16.120
Hmm, hmm.

00:25:16.120 --> 00:25:21.120
I wonder where it is, er, now I, I've forgotten about that.

00:25:21.120 --> 00:25:25.120
I wonder where that is now.

00:25:25.120 --> 00:25:29.120
Yeah, now I wonder where that is.

00:25:29.120 --> 00:25:31.120
You've got me thinking now.

00:25:31.120 --> 00:25:32.120
Ha ha ha.

00:25:32.120 --> 00:25:34.120
I'll be trying to explore where it is.

00:25:34.120 --> 00:25:39.120
So would they, would the WI rent it out, or would they take it out to people and say,

00:25:39.120 --> 00:25:41.120
do the canning for people?

00:25:41.120 --> 00:25:44.120
Er, I couldn't, I wouldn't, I can't say that.

00:25:44.120 --> 00:25:48.120
I mean, erm, I know we used to borrow it and do our own.

00:25:48.120 --> 00:25:52.120
At least Mother Prosser did more than I did, but I'd give a hand, you know.

00:25:52.120 --> 00:25:56.120
But erm, that's interesting how you brought up that canning machine.

00:25:56.120 --> 00:25:57.120
I'm not going to bother you now.

00:25:57.120 --> 00:25:58.120
I'd be worried about that.

00:25:58.120 --> 00:25:59.120
Ha ha ha.

00:25:59.120 --> 00:26:01.120
It'd be lovely if it's still around somewhere.

00:26:01.120 --> 00:26:02.120
Yes.

00:26:02.120 --> 00:26:04.120
Yes, it would, wouldn't it?

00:26:04.120 --> 00:26:07.120
And it's still going, the St. Brides WI?

00:26:07.120 --> 00:26:10.120
St. Brides, no, no, it's folded up a long time ago.

00:26:10.120 --> 00:26:11.120
Oh really?

00:26:11.120 --> 00:26:12.120
Yes, yes, yes.

00:26:12.120 --> 00:26:13.120
Oh, that's a shame.

00:26:13.120 --> 00:26:17.120
So a lot of the people from there now come to Peterstone, and this is why I'm rather

00:26:17.120 --> 00:26:20.120
upset that Peterstone is talking about folding up.

00:26:20.120 --> 00:26:21.120
Oh.

00:26:21.120 --> 00:26:26.120
I mean, the secretary, she's moving away down to Swansea, well that's why I'm there.

00:26:26.120 --> 00:26:31.120
The president, she did say that she'd do it for another two years.

00:26:31.120 --> 00:26:35.120
Well, the two years has come up now, and no one else wants to take the responsibility.

00:26:35.120 --> 00:26:36.120
That's such a shame.

00:26:36.120 --> 00:26:37.120
It is a shame.

00:26:37.120 --> 00:26:38.120
It is a shame.

00:26:38.120 --> 00:26:40.120
And it's been going how long?

00:26:40.120 --> 00:26:42.120
Well, I've been down there 62 years.

00:26:42.120 --> 00:26:44.120
That's phenomenal, Margaret.

00:26:44.120 --> 00:26:46.120
And it was on a long time before that.

00:26:46.120 --> 00:26:47.120
Oh.

00:26:47.120 --> 00:26:48.120
Yes, it's sad really.

00:26:48.120 --> 00:26:50.120
How many members have you got down there?

00:26:50.120 --> 00:27:00.120
There's, from St. Brides area, around Asda, where people live, I expect there's 14 people

00:27:00.120 --> 00:27:02.120
come from that area.

00:27:02.120 --> 00:27:07.120
And it seems such a shame that, you know, no one will take it on.

00:27:07.120 --> 00:27:08.120
After all that time?

00:27:08.120 --> 00:27:09.120
Yeah, it is.

00:27:09.120 --> 00:27:15.120
Because I was president for about seven years after Mother Pross has given it up, I don't

00:27:15.120 --> 00:27:16.120
know how long she was.

00:27:16.120 --> 00:27:18.120
But no, it's quite sad.

00:27:18.120 --> 00:27:21.120
I was quite upset about it really.

00:27:21.120 --> 00:27:28.120
But I'm hoping that I might join Kevin Madley, Michael Stoneman, which is nearer.

00:27:28.120 --> 00:27:29.120
Yeah.

00:27:29.120 --> 00:27:32.120
But the distance didn't make any difference to me.

00:27:32.120 --> 00:27:34.120
It's a longevity though, isn't it?

00:27:34.120 --> 00:27:35.120
Winds and weathers.

00:27:35.120 --> 00:27:36.120
Yeah.

00:27:36.120 --> 00:27:38.120
Pick up a couple of ladies from Ashfield on the way down.

00:27:38.120 --> 00:27:39.120
Oh, how sweet.

00:27:39.120 --> 00:27:40.120
Yes, you just enjoy it.

00:27:40.120 --> 00:27:42.120
That's how it goes, isn't it?

00:27:42.120 --> 00:27:47.120
So you said Mother Pross used to can fruit.

00:27:47.120 --> 00:27:48.120
Yes.

00:27:48.120 --> 00:27:50.120
Where did her fruit come from?

00:27:50.120 --> 00:27:53.120
Oh, well, she had, we had plum trees.

00:27:53.120 --> 00:27:58.120
You know, we had trees, we had plum trees and we had a couple of trees around here.

00:27:58.120 --> 00:27:59.120
Yeah.

00:27:59.120 --> 00:28:00.120
Plum trees and things.

00:28:00.120 --> 00:28:02.120
And well, that was our garden then.

00:28:02.120 --> 00:28:03.120
Yeah.

00:28:03.120 --> 00:28:08.120
You know, and then we'd have beans and stuff like that, you know, to roast it.

00:28:09.120 --> 00:28:14.120
But yeah, I've forgotten about that canning machine.

00:28:14.120 --> 00:28:16.120
So what was the process then?

00:28:16.120 --> 00:28:18.120
So you'd pick the fruit and then wash it?

00:28:18.120 --> 00:28:19.120
Yes.

00:28:19.120 --> 00:28:20.120
And then make a syrup.

00:28:20.120 --> 00:28:21.120
Yeah.

00:28:21.120 --> 00:28:23.120
And then put it in the tins.

00:28:23.120 --> 00:28:26.120
And then with the machine you'd seal it all.

00:28:26.120 --> 00:28:28.120
And that would be a tinned fruit.

00:28:28.120 --> 00:28:30.120
Gosh, and that would last all the winter?

00:28:30.120 --> 00:28:35.120
Well, yes, if you know, you make as much as you can, you know, or we could.

00:28:35.120 --> 00:28:39.120
And yes, gosh, I'm glad you thought about the canning machine.

00:28:39.120 --> 00:28:41.120
You've got me worried now.

00:28:41.120 --> 00:28:43.120
Well, it's come up a few times, you see.

00:28:43.120 --> 00:28:44.120
So I thought, I'm curious.

00:28:44.120 --> 00:28:45.120
Yes.

00:28:45.120 --> 00:28:47.120
I've never heard of a canning machine before.

00:28:47.120 --> 00:28:50.120
And that St. Bride's WI has a canning machine.

00:28:50.120 --> 00:28:52.120
It just sounds really resourceful to me.

00:28:52.120 --> 00:28:54.120
Yes, that's right.

00:28:54.120 --> 00:28:56.120
Yes, yes.

00:28:56.120 --> 00:28:58.120
I wonder where that is now.

00:28:59.120 --> 00:29:07.120
Did the WI, because in the past the WI has been absolutely fantastic at recording local people and their memories,

00:29:07.120 --> 00:29:11.120
did the St. Bride's WI ever do anything like that?

00:29:11.120 --> 00:29:17.120
No, they folded up, as I said, and a couple of them came from there then, which are a few more now,

00:29:17.120 --> 00:29:22.120
because the president it is now, she lives in one of the houses by our stairs.

00:29:22.120 --> 00:29:25.120
And of course a couple of her friends have come as well.

00:29:26.120 --> 00:29:30.120
As I say, I was quite upset last week when I knew it was going to fold up.

00:29:30.120 --> 00:29:31.120
Oh, that is upsetting.

00:29:31.120 --> 00:29:33.120
Yes, it is.

00:29:33.120 --> 00:29:35.120
But there we are, people are not interested.

00:29:35.120 --> 00:29:38.120
You can't force people to be.

00:29:38.120 --> 00:29:39.120
You can't.

00:29:39.120 --> 00:29:41.120
You can try and encourage.

00:29:43.120 --> 00:29:49.120
So as a young woman, a young wife, was it part of one's social life, the WI?

00:29:49.120 --> 00:29:51.120
It was, really.

00:29:51.120 --> 00:29:55.120
Yes, I went up to London for the two AGMs.

00:29:56.120 --> 00:30:03.120
The WI was something that you did as a young wife, and you have continued to do for a long time.

00:30:03.120 --> 00:30:05.120
Yes, yes, yes.

00:30:05.120 --> 00:30:07.120
Yes, I enjoyed WI.

00:30:07.120 --> 00:30:13.120
I went to London to the AGM on two occasions, which is up at the Albert Hall,

00:30:13.120 --> 00:30:17.120
and that was very interesting, where they come from all over the country.

00:30:17.120 --> 00:30:20.120
It has gone back a bit.

00:30:20.120 --> 00:30:25.120
But you know, what struck me about down on the moors there,

00:30:25.120 --> 00:30:27.120
that it's quite a different landscape, isn't it?

00:30:27.120 --> 00:30:29.120
It's flat, all the water courses.

00:30:29.120 --> 00:30:30.120
Oh, yes, yes.

00:30:30.120 --> 00:30:32.120
Was that a challenge in some way?

00:30:32.120 --> 00:30:37.120
I don't know whether you were a friend, because there's people living in the church now,

00:30:37.120 --> 00:30:44.120
the church was, and on about, what, what am I, five foot, am I five foot or nothing?

00:30:44.120 --> 00:30:49.120
Except about, well, I should know the possible, where the Greek flood was.

00:30:49.120 --> 00:30:50.120
Yes, yes.

00:30:50.120 --> 00:30:56.120
Yes, and the bank, you can see the bank, now we're one of the fields of one of the farms up,

00:30:56.120 --> 00:30:58.120
as you go down the road a bit.

00:30:58.120 --> 00:30:59.120
Yes.

00:30:59.120 --> 00:31:06.120
Yes, well, I think I'm right in saying, the water more or less came up nearly up to Cattleden.

00:31:06.120 --> 00:31:09.120
Yeah, it was, yeah, because it goes down, doesn't it, apparently?

00:31:09.120 --> 00:31:11.120
Yeah, yeah, it's very low, very low.

00:31:11.120 --> 00:31:13.120
Did you ever experience flooding there?

00:31:13.120 --> 00:31:18.120
No, no, the rains would fill up quite a bit, you know, but no, no,

00:31:18.120 --> 00:31:20.120
we never had any flooding as such, no.

00:31:20.120 --> 00:31:25.120
What was it like having young children around those things, though, was it ever a worry?

00:31:25.120 --> 00:31:31.120
Oh, yes, yes, now the neighbours on that farm down to, what's the farm then,

00:31:31.120 --> 00:31:36.120
they lost a child that drowned in the water.

00:31:36.120 --> 00:31:42.120
And also, instant brides, the child drowned in some brides in the rain.

00:31:42.120 --> 00:31:43.120
Oh, really?

00:31:43.120 --> 00:31:46.120
Yes, yes, but I suppose you get,

00:31:46.120 --> 00:31:50.120
I suppose if you're born down there, you get used to it.

00:31:50.120 --> 00:31:54.120
I know the one that came down, the one further on down the road,

00:31:54.120 --> 00:31:58.120
was from London, came down to see the sister,

00:31:58.120 --> 00:32:03.120
came down and brought the little one, of course, went down the steps and down to the rain there,

00:32:03.120 --> 00:32:05.120
you know, which is very sad, very sad.

00:32:05.120 --> 00:32:06.120
Oh, gosh, that's so sad, isn't it?

00:32:06.120 --> 00:32:10.120
Terrible, terrible. Yes, but...

00:32:10.120 --> 00:32:15.120
When you first went to Sleuth's Farm, was there electricity and stuff?

00:32:15.120 --> 00:32:20.120
Yes, yes, yes, yes, yes, because when I lived in Langorce, we had no electricity.

00:32:20.120 --> 00:32:21.120
No, no.

00:32:21.120 --> 00:32:24.120
I got the Aladdin lamp there, the hanging Aladdin lamp,

00:32:24.120 --> 00:32:28.120
and I've got a little table lamp that's in there, that's with oil,

00:32:28.120 --> 00:32:33.120
and we didn't have any hot water, cold water or anything like that.

00:32:33.120 --> 00:32:38.120
Can you talk about the winter of 47? What was the winter of 62, 63 like?

00:32:38.120 --> 00:32:40.120
I was down here then, of course.

00:32:40.120 --> 00:32:41.120
Oh, here?

00:32:41.120 --> 00:32:43.120
Yes, yes, it was bad then.

00:32:43.120 --> 00:32:47.120
We used to go up to Castleton with the tractor

00:32:47.120 --> 00:32:51.120
to have the lorry to come down, you know, to bring it down.

00:32:51.120 --> 00:32:52.120
Really?

00:32:52.120 --> 00:32:57.120
And then in the evenings, a couple of the locals there, the youngsters,

00:32:57.120 --> 00:33:04.120
they'd take me down the six-pouse on a big boat, drag it down the road, you know.

00:33:04.120 --> 00:33:10.120
Oh, yes, we had quite a lot of snow. Yes, yes, yes, but we had more when we were in Langorce.

00:33:10.120 --> 00:33:17.120
I remember seeing on Penavan, down one of the crevices in June, there was still snow.

00:33:17.120 --> 00:33:19.120
Really? My goodness. I can see that now.

00:33:19.120 --> 00:33:21.120
It went on and on and on, didn't it?

00:33:21.120 --> 00:33:22.120
Yes, it did, it did.

00:33:22.120 --> 00:33:25.120
Did anyone ever go skating on the Reens or anything like that?

00:33:25.120 --> 00:33:30.120
On the lake. Oh, sorry, on Langorce Lake they used to go, but I mean,

00:33:30.120 --> 00:33:35.120
well, it was frozen over and a motorbike went across, and it's never known before.

00:33:35.120 --> 00:33:36.120
Really?

00:33:36.120 --> 00:33:37.120
It went across the other side.

00:33:37.120 --> 00:33:39.120
I've never heard that before.

00:33:39.120 --> 00:33:43.120
I think they did. Yes, I should say, but many did freeze, didn't they?

00:33:43.120 --> 00:33:44.120
Yes.

00:33:44.120 --> 00:33:49.120
You know, it's just, and yeah, we used to go, we used to go and,

00:33:49.120 --> 00:33:53.120
a crowd of us were really into Langorce, we used to take one of these little boats.

00:33:53.120 --> 00:34:00.120
We used to go down to the other side of Langorce, Langasty, and I don't know, even with Langorce.

00:34:00.120 --> 00:34:05.120
And if you look across there, there's a little hole, about three feet from the end of the river,

00:34:05.120 --> 00:34:10.120
and Langorce, and we used to go across there to dances,

00:34:10.120 --> 00:34:15.120
and we'd take one of these skiff boats, you know, and we used to row across there.

00:34:15.120 --> 00:34:16.120
Did you really?

00:34:16.120 --> 00:34:17.120
Yeah.

00:34:17.120 --> 00:34:18.120
That's quite some distance.

00:34:18.120 --> 00:34:22.120
Yes, it was really, back when you were younger, I noticed distance too.

00:34:22.120 --> 00:34:23.120
I wonder now.

00:34:23.120 --> 00:34:28.120
And we used to tether it there and walk up these two or three years, go to the dance,

00:34:28.120 --> 00:34:30.120
come back, then and row back.

00:34:30.120 --> 00:34:34.120
My goodness, imagine if my daughter was doing that, I'd be, you know,

00:34:34.120 --> 00:34:35.120
Yeah, or what we used to do.

00:34:35.120 --> 00:34:36.120
Or what we used to do.

00:34:36.120 --> 00:34:39.120
Yeah, what we used to do then, years ago, when we were young.

00:34:39.120 --> 00:34:45.120
Do you remember the, did you ever help with haymaking as a young farmer's wife?

00:34:45.120 --> 00:34:50.120
Well, yes, dry the tractor perhaps and that, you know, the baling.

00:34:50.120 --> 00:34:56.120
And of course, we had a photograph, I don't know, I might have got a photograph here,

00:34:56.120 --> 00:34:59.120
