He was another character.

00:47:04.120 --> 00:47:09.120
I'm trying to think of his name.

00:47:09.120 --> 00:47:12.120
He lived in a barn.

00:47:12.120 --> 00:47:17.120
I don't like to use the word tramp, but kind of like just somebody who used to...

00:47:17.120 --> 00:47:21.120
Yes, they were kind of a tramp type of person, you know.

00:47:21.120 --> 00:47:23.120
Billy Mitch, that was down there.

00:47:23.120 --> 00:47:28.120
That's right, and Dennis used to be in this one, in our barn over there.

00:47:28.120 --> 00:47:36.120
No trouble, I mean, you know, actually I think Father Prosser went over there one day,

00:47:36.120 --> 00:47:38.120
and he died in the Llasnym, so...

00:47:38.120 --> 00:47:39.120
Really?

00:47:39.120 --> 00:47:41.120
To get the police and all up his back.

00:47:41.120 --> 00:47:42.120
Yeah.

00:47:43.120 --> 00:47:46.120
But, no, there were characters about then, weren't there?

00:47:46.120 --> 00:47:47.120
Yeah.

00:47:47.120 --> 00:47:51.120
Years ago, like that.

00:47:51.120 --> 00:47:54.120
I can see them, I can place them now.

00:47:54.120 --> 00:47:56.120
It's gone back a little while.

00:47:56.120 --> 00:47:59.120
Yes, Dennis and Billy Mitch used to call him.

00:47:59.120 --> 00:48:04.120
And they reckoned that if the airplanes were coming over during the war,

00:48:04.120 --> 00:48:07.120
because that was when he was there during the war,

00:48:07.120 --> 00:48:11.120
he'd turn his pipe upside down, in cases.

00:48:12.120 --> 00:48:14.120
Oh, isn't that lovely?

00:48:14.120 --> 00:48:18.120
It's a compliment when you think it was a thing, because they might see his pipe.

00:48:18.120 --> 00:48:20.120
Oh, right.

00:48:21.120 --> 00:48:23.120
Oh, Jesus, really funny.

00:48:23.120 --> 00:48:28.120
Someone was telling me, now, where was it now?

00:48:28.120 --> 00:48:30.120
I can't remember.

00:48:31.120 --> 00:48:33.120
Oh, something about that...

00:48:33.120 --> 00:48:36.120
Was it St. Brides, or was it somewhere else there?

00:48:36.120 --> 00:48:41.120
I might be wrong, but on the Sunday, the pubs used to be closed in Wales.

00:48:41.120 --> 00:48:43.120
This is when the border was different,

00:48:43.120 --> 00:48:47.120
so people used to flood over to here to use the pubs on the Sunday.

00:48:47.120 --> 00:48:48.120
Is that right?

00:48:48.120 --> 00:48:50.120
Maybe I've got that wrong.

00:48:52.120 --> 00:48:54.120
No, they used to...

00:48:54.120 --> 00:48:57.120
There was a law, wasn't there, where the pubs used to close on a Sunday,

00:48:57.120 --> 00:48:59.120
a lot of places.

00:48:59.120 --> 00:49:03.120
But I can't remember where that was.

00:49:03.120 --> 00:49:05.120
I might have got that wrong, actually.

00:49:05.120 --> 00:49:09.120
I feel very sad, really, the six bars was closed.

00:49:09.120 --> 00:49:11.120
Yeah.

00:49:11.120 --> 00:49:15.120
There were two cottages at the side of that.

00:49:15.120 --> 00:49:19.120
Was it a popular pub?

00:49:19.120 --> 00:49:21.120
Oh, yes.

00:49:21.120 --> 00:49:25.120
We've had a lot of lovely times down there, especially Christmas time.

00:49:25.120 --> 00:49:28.120
We'd go down there, and somebody would be playing the organ,

00:49:28.120 --> 00:49:31.120
and we'd have a good old sing-song and that.

00:49:31.120 --> 00:49:33.120
Yeah.

00:49:33.120 --> 00:49:35.120
Oh, I think I've got a photograph.

00:49:35.120 --> 00:49:37.120
I'm boring you with these photographs.

00:49:37.120 --> 00:49:39.120
You are not. I love photographs, Margaret.

00:49:39.120 --> 00:49:41.120
I really do love photographs.

00:49:45.120 --> 00:49:49.120
This is the six bars with all the horses.

00:49:49.120 --> 00:49:51.120
No, that's interesting.

00:49:51.120 --> 00:49:53.120
I think I might have seen that photograph before.

00:49:53.120 --> 00:49:55.120
Have you, maybe?

00:49:55.120 --> 00:49:58.120
Erm, no, I think...

00:49:58.120 --> 00:50:00.120
He was no master.

